<@U1S5GKTHQ> When you have a minute, will you knock up the level on the character count restrictions to what is shown in the character count comps (<https://drive.google.com/open?id=0B1KFvQr_SwVvcHd6Qy1DdFFwdWM>) Ok if it's a tmrw thing. Not sure what you have on your plate at the moment

Oh good! Cool. Yep- tmrw works
<@U0B9N0HF0> Here’s an idea for some image-too-small copy: “Heads up, the image you uploaded is very small. Consider uploading a larger image for the best wall display experience."
I like it! Strikes a good balance and tone
Thanks! Thoughts from anyone else?
I’ll chime in.
elisecramer: I worry the text is a little long for a dialog box.  Also we’re assuming that it’s a “very” small image.  Sorry, not trying to nitpick these are the mportant details.
Oh gotcha. Didn’t realize this was a dialogue box. What are the actions on the dialogue box? I imagined that this text just appeared in red when they uploaded the file
Are we assuming it’s a “very” small image? I thought we knew
Your text asumes it’s a very small image
it might just be slightly smaller than spec, so we can eliminate the word “very” though using the word helps the overall tone so it’s a tough edit
and you’re right, it can be error text and not system dialog but in either case it’s a tad long.
I’ll trim down the length, yea I was trying to figure out if we have to assume it’s a “very small image” or if we know that to be true—which it sounds like we do
Let’s just take the second sentence: “Consider uploading a larger image for a better wall experience"
When I saw it on the testing screens, that image felt super tiny—was trying to have the copy convey how small that image is going to look if they stick with it. I’ll edit it out for length though

we’ll know the size but we shouldn’t try to present specific copy for smaller or almost there imagery.  i’d just eliminate the word small to save on word count and be more generalized.  but your tone is perfect.
and i do think this should be a system dialog box, we want to catch people’s attention.  rred error text would be if we rejected it.
What would the action on the box be?
word
clicking “Ok"
hm no, maybe two buttons.  Like “Proceed Anyway” and “Go back” as options
Where would proceed anyway take them?
Happy to chat in person about this if we want. I think a dialogue box needs a thought-out flow
i agree, currently multitasking.  want your opinion on this anyway
i’ll come to you
I do like the "Heads up," intro though. Seems as though it would be a little less frustrating to see over and over again?
